<HEAD>Pope Arrives in Cape Verde on First Stop of Sixth African Tour</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with pope's arrival, remarks.
Pickup 4th pvs, ``The countries...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAL ISLAND, Cape Verde (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II praised the
Christian heritage of this African nation today as he began an
eight-day tour of the impoverished Sahel region, his sixth
pilgrimage to Africa.
   The pope flew from Rome in a special Alitalia Airbus to Amilcar
Cabral international airport on the 10-island archipelago off
Africa's northwest coast. After two days in the former Portuguese
colony, he heads to Guinea Bissau, Mali, Burkina Faso and Chad.
   In brief remarks in Portuguese, the pope referred to the
predominantly Roman Catholic islands as a country of ``ancient
Christianity at the gates of continental Africa'' and wished
``grace, salvation and peace'' on Cape Verdians and the many who
emigrated abroad.
   After greetings from several thousand well-wishers, the pope
transferred to a smaller plane for a 40-minute flight to Praia for
the official welcoming ceremony.
   Islanders were out all day sweeping the sand and dust from the
streets blown by strong winds gusting across the archipelago.
   The trip is the 45th foreign voyage of the pope's 11-year
pontificate.
   The countries in the sub-Saharan semi-arid region stretching
across western and central Africa are among the world's poorest,
with millions of people living on the edge of starvation.
   The pope is expected to renew an appeal he made 10 years ago for
international aid to help save sub-Saharan Africa from its chronic
problems of poverty, hunger, disease and encroaching deserts.
   ``This is the poorest part of Africa and the pope will discuss
the realities of these countries,'' said Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro.
   The visit comes at a time when African government and church
leaders are concerned that Western aid and development funds will
be redirected from Africa to the new democrtic movements in Eastern
Europe.
   ``The interest of the Western world is focused on the East, and
there is a risk of forgetting to save one part of humanity that
would fall back into misery,'' Cardinal Paul Zoungrana of Burkina
Faso said in an interview with the Italian Catholic magazine 30
Giorni (30 Days).
   ``This is not the moment to abandon Africa,'' he said. ``The
pope can use his moral strength and attract the attention of the
whole world.''
   Noting that the Polish-born pope himself comes from Eastern
Europe, the cardinal said, ``If a new problem arises, you can't
forget the old ones. And if it's a pope from the East who reminds
us, the world will take note.''
   In a special supplement on the papal trip, the Vatican newspaper
L'Osservatore Romano decried the world's ``indifference'' towards
Africa's problems.
   ``While the eyes of the world are still fixed on the
extraordinary events of Eastern Europe, the heart of the church now
looks elsewhere ... to the vast territory of suffering that is
Africa,'' the newspaper said.
   A centerpiece of the pope's trip will be a ceremony Monday in
Ouagadougou, capital of Burkina Faso, marking the 10th anniversary
of John Paul's appeal for the Sahel in which he declared: ``I can
not remain silent while my brothers and sisters are in danger.''
   The appeal led to the creation in 1984 of the John Paul II
Foundation for the Sahel, funded primarily by contributions from
Catholics in West Germany and sponsoring agricultural and
development projects in the region.
   John Paul, who is scheduled to make another trip to Africa later
this year, is particularly interested in Africa because of the
rapid growth of Catholicism on the continent. The African church
counts more than 75 million followers today, or about 13 percent of
the total population, compared to 1 percent at the turn of the
century.
   About 90 percent of Cape Verde's population of 360,000 is Roman
Catholic, the highest percentage in Africa. However, Catholics are
a small minority in the other countries on the tour, ranging from
less than 1 percent in Mali to 9 percent in Burkina Faso.
   While Cape Verde is the most prosperous of the five nations,
more than 400,000 islanders _ greater than the current population _
have emigrated in recent decades to the United States and Europe in
search of jobs and a better life.
</TEXT>
