<HEAD>Pope Tells Burkina Faso Catholics to Resist Contraception</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with pope's remarks in Burkina
Faso; picks up 9th pvs: I rejoice ...
^By STEPHEN R. WILSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II told Roman
Catholics today to resist abortion and contraception as they try to
improve living conditions in this impoverished West African country.
   Celebrating Mass outside the capital at a national pilgrimage
site, the pope said the church and its members should work to build
up the country ``on the basis of respect for the human person and
the family.
   ``Human life is inviolable, the right to life should be defended
ceaselessly,'' John Paul said.
   He said life should be protected ``from conception until natural
death'' and that couples should live ``a responsible fatherhood and
motherhood.''
   He said couples must resist ``invasion of methods which go
against the dignity of the woman and do not honor the man. I appeal
to all lay people to fight for the sanctification of the family.''
   The Roman Catholic Church rejects artificial birth control and
the church here has resisted government birth control plans.
   The pope arrived here from Mali on the fourth leg of an
eight-day tour of five African nations. About 9 percent of Burkina
Faso's 8.5 million people are Roman Catholics, more than a third
are Moslems and most of the rest are animist.
   On his way from the airport to the Mass site, the pope's
motorcade passed tens of thousands of people gathered by the
roadside in front of thatched huts and concrete hovels. A steady
wind from the Sahara desert blew sand and dust.
   The country has been blighted by drought and expanding desert
and the average per capita income is around $200.
   John Paul was greeted upon arrival from Mali by President Blaise
Compaore, who took power in a 1987 coup in which his predecessor,
Thomas Sankara, was killed.
   Africa is Catholicism's fastest growing church, with more 75
million adherents. The Vatican expects to count 100 million African
faithful by the year 2000.
   However, Islam is a major challenger for converts, and the
Catholic church is increasingly worried by the spread of Islamic
fundamentalism in some areas of Africa.
   In Mali, the pope celebrated a Mass attended by 15,000
Christians and 10,000 Moslems.
   ``I rejoice that a climate of understanding reigns between the
Moslem and Catholic communities in Mali,'' the pope said in his
homily during the Mass at Bamako's soccer stadium. ``Dialogue
between Moslems and Christians is more necessary than ever.''
   As the pope toured the stadium in an open Mercedes, both Moslems
and Catholics stood, waved and cheered.
   About 1 percent of Mali's 8 million people are Catholics, while
Moslems account for 70 percent. Most of the rest are animists.
   ``I hope that the dialogue between Moslems and Catholics
improves even more and favors constructive cooperation,'' John Paul
said.
   Earlier in the day, the pope spoke of the church's concern over
intolerance toward Catholics in some other countries in Africa
without naming any individual nations.
   He also urged Catholics to recognize and respect ``the authentic
religious values'' of Moslems.
   ``Dialogue with them is not always easy or desired by everyone,
and it is sometimes difficult to find a common language or
representatives to talk to each other,'' he said in a speech to
Mali's bishops.
</TEXT>
